A single class with a `code: string` field lets any caller accept any value at compile time — nothing stops you from writing `if (err.code === "Declined")` when the real string is `"DECLINE"`. Three `Data.TaggedError` classes put the discriminant in the type system: `Effect.catchTag("Decline", ...)` won't compile if the tag is mistyped, and callers who forget a branch see the unhandled tag still in the E channel. The cost is one class per error; the payoff is exhaustiveness and IDE autocomplete on every branch.

